  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 10-20 years per money laundering offense\n- Potential concurrent or consecutive sentencing\n- Enhanced penalties if part of larger criminal enterprises\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n\n3. Additional potential consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\n4. Specific statutes governing penalties:\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (money laundering criminal statute)\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (monetary transaction in criminally derived property)\n\n5. Sentencing factors:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific criminal intent\n- Prior criminal history\n- Role in the laundering scheme\n\nExact penalties can vary based on specific circumstances and prosecutorial discretion. Consulting a legal professional would provide the most precise information for a specific situation.",
